Process called "build_print_statement" takes expression as Integer, continuing as Integer, line as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs the AST_PRINT_STATEMENT (= 9015) node representing an
    `Alert <expr>` / `Display <expr>` print statement. This mirrors the
    stage1 monolith's statement_create_print (parser.runa:4288): a single
    expression child plus a no-trailing-newline modifier flag (Task #428).
    The modular AST uses the uniform ASTNode layout, so the expression is
    attached as child 0 (exactly as build_return_statement does) and the
    `continuing` flag is stored in the node value slot (offset 40), the
    only free slot on the base node. HIR lowering reads child 0 for the
    expression and the value slot for the flag, then desugars the print
    into a direct call to the print_string / print_integer runtime helper
    (or the _nonl variant when continuing is set).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single create_ast_node call with type 9015. The expression is attached
    as a child via ast_node_add_child (a print statement always carries a
    value expression, but the child is guarded for defensiveness so a
    malformed print still produces a valid node for downstream diagnostics).
    The continuing flag is written into the value slot via
    ast_node_set_value with value_type tag 2 (integer flag), matching the
    integer-flag convention used elsewhere for non-string node values.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). One node allocation, at most one child-list append, and one
    value-slot write. Cold path -- invoked once per print source construct.
    @End Performance_Hints

    Note: AST_PRINT_STATEMENT = 9015
    Let node be proc create_ast_node from AST with 9015, line, 1

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If expression is not equal to 0:
        proc ast_node_add_child from AST with node, expression
    End If

    Note: Store the continuing (no-trailing-newline) flag in the value slot.
    Note: value_type tag 2 marks this as an integer flag rather than a string.
    proc ast_node_set_value from AST with node, continuing, 2

    Return node
End Process

Process called "build_block_statement" takes statements as Integer, statement_count as Integer, line as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Build a block statement AST node

    Note: AST_BLOCK_STATEMENT = 2018
    Let node be proc create_ast_node from AST with 2018, line, 1

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If statements is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        Loop forever:
            If i is greater than or equal to statement_count:
                Break
            End If

            Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
            proc ast_node_add_child from AST with node, stmt
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Process called "build_unsafe_block" takes body as Integer, line as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs the AST_UNSAFE_BLOCK (= 2019) node that represents an
    `Unsafe Block: ... End Unsafe` source construct. The body parameter
    is attached as the single child; HIR lowering walks the child to
    produce the inner block and brackets the body with
    enter_unsafe / leave_unsafe on the HIR builder context.

    The AST_UNSAFE_BLOCK type code is the integration point with the
    HIR builder: any code path that lowers AST nodes must dispatch on
    type 2019 to enter the unsafe-permission scope before recursing.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single call to create_ast_node with type 2019. On success, attaches
    the body as a child node via ast_node_add_child; the body is
    optional (allowing a malformed/empty Unsafe Block to still produce
    a valid AST node for downstream error reporting). The line argument
    is preserved on the node so HIR-stage rejection diagnostics report
    the user-visible source location.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). One node allocation plus at most one child-list append.
    Cold path -- invoked once per Unsafe Block source construct.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The Q4 enforcement chain (parser -> AST -> HIR rejection) depends
    on this constructor producing exactly node-type 2019. The literal
    constant is the contract between this Process and hir_builder's
    dispatch table; changing one without the other would silently
    disable unsafe-external rejection. The line argument flows into
    diagnostics; an attacker-controlled line value can mislead error
    reporting but cannot bypass the semantic check, which keys on the
    callee identifier, not the source line.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let node be proc create_ast_node from AST with 2019, line, 1

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc ast_node_add_child from AST with node, body
    End If

    Return node
End Process

